			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-weight: bold">As of December 18, 2003, the developers at EQ have made changes to the way Reclaim Energy works.  It now returns 75% of the mana used to summon the pet.  When Improved Reclaim is trained, that number is raised to 95%.  As a result, Reclaim Chaining is now made available to magicians of all levels.  I have modified my original Reclaim Chaining guide to incorporate these changes.</span>
<br />

<br />
There are really two major subtopics on this particular subject. The first will be solo, the second will be grouping with at least one more magician.
<br />

<br />
There are certain essentials if you wish to start practicing this somewhat offbeat chaining method. For starters, the minimum requirements are as follows:
<br />

<br />
1. You will need access to the Reclaim Energy spell, whether it is from memming it from your spellbook or right clicking from an item.  Overall, you are best with an instaclick Reclaim Energy item, such as your Temple of Solusek Ro focus items (Stein of Ulissa, Shovel of Ponz, Broom of Trilon, Torch of Alna), Staves of Elemental Mastery, or Gloves of Dark Summoning from Vex Thall.
<br />

<br />
2. Particularly when soloing, you will need to have access to your highest level Earth pet spell. The Earth pet root spell is almost essential when soloing. Access to the Malaise line of spells is also extremely helpful as well.
<br />

<br />
3. Although not required, it is helpful to have a Summoning Efficiency item, as well as a Summoning Haste item. For AA skills, Improved Reclaim, Quick Summoning and Elemental Pact are helpful as well.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">SOLOING</span>
<br />

<br />
1. As was already mentioned, pet root is practically essential, so have your highest level Earth pet memmed. Also memorize your highest level Malaise-type spell, if available.
<br />

<br />
2. Pull your mob with a low aggro spell.
<br />

<br />
3. Send pet in and make sure you cast your highest level Malaise-type spell, if available, to minimize mob resisting the pet's root spell.  (Special note:  Before level 24, we have no access to the Malaise line of spells.  As a result, your mob choices are critical.  I highly recommend pulling the lowest level dark blues you can find to assure that your pet's root spell sticks for its full duration)
<br />

<br />
4. Watch carefully how quickly the pet is losing hit points. If the pet is losing hit points rather quickly, you may have to reclaim rather quickly as well.
<br />

<br />
5. Ideally (and this is not always possible, particularly with giant mobs that have an extended reach) you will want to stand close enough to the mob that you can see whether or not the pet root landed. You will see the message "&lt;mob name&gt; sinks into the ground" or "&lt;mob name&gt; is entrapped by the Rathe" in the case of Rathe's Son.
<br />

<br />
6. At some point you will need to reclaim your pet. Against some mobs, it's when the pet is below 30% hit points, against other mobs it may be as early as the pet's second cast of its root spell. You will need to time this recast with the pet's landing of its root spell. The moment the spell lands, immediately right-click your Reclaim Energy spell. The mob will be rooted in place, giving you time to recast your pet. (Special note:  If you do not have access to an instacast Reclaim Energy effect, you will need to cast your level 1 Reclaim Energy spell.  It is a 2.5 second spell, meaning you will have to practice timing the cast of the spell so the pet disappears almost immediately after the pet casts its root spell.  Earth pets cast their root spell every 6 seconds (but they sometimes miss a cycle), so just after the last root cast, count to 5, then start casting Reclaim Energy.  If the pet misses his cast, interrupt your spell by ducking, and start again. )
<br />

<br />
7. Pet root lasts as long as 18 seconds, but it could potentially last less time. For this reason it is strongly recommended to reduce the cast time on your pet summons (Summoning Haste item and/or Quick Summoning skill, summoned spell haste ring, cleric buff, etc.) The moment you reclaim your pet, immediately start resummoning. While resummoning, it is a good idea to have your pet attack command ready. The fastest way to do this, in my experience, is to type out /pet kill &lt;first few letters of the mob's name&gt; then hit enter as soon as the pet is summoned. For example, if the mob's name is "a Shimmering Rockfiend" then your typed command will look something like this: /pet kill a_sh . If mana permits, you may rebuff your new pet.
<br />

<br />
8. At some point during the fight, you will need to do at least some direct damage to the mob to prevent your pet from taking 75% of the experience. Burst of Flame and Shock of Blades work for this, or you can use a heavier nuke if you so desire. If using a heavier nuke, be aware that it may take a little time for the pet to regain aggro or land a root, so it will put you at greater risk than using a small nuke.
<br />

<br />
9. Once the mob is dead, loot at will. If you meditate while the pet is fighting you will discover that you will have consumed very little mana, or even gained some, so meditating between fights is totally unnecessary. You can immediately pull again.</span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Jochan Galadar on Wed Dec 24, 2003 6:13 am; edited 4 times in total</span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
