			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="text-decoration: underline">SPECIAL CIRCUMSTANCES: Enrage</span>
<br />

<br />
Against enraging mobs, it may prove difficult to keep pets on the mob for very long. Enrage is an effective defense against pets, who characteristically hit rather fast.
<br />

<br />
There are a couple of effective ways to deal with enrage. The first is to have your heaviest nuke being cast just before the mob enrages. This is much easier the more magicians you add to the group. The second is to have Pet Discipline trained. Have these two commands on a hotkey: /pet sit, then /pet hold on the next line. Pet will stay in melee range of the mob, but the pet is taking no riposte damage. You can then use a smaller nuke, if you desire, and cast just after enrage starts.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">SPECIAL CIRCUMSTANCES: mobs that summon</span>
<br />

<br />
In multiple magician groups, being summoned will almost never be an issue, as long as there is a pet on the mob, and nuking is tightly controlled. Solo you will need to use some special tactics.
<br />

<br />
1. You will need to have your pet summoning hasted to the max, meaning 5 seconds. This can be done by maxing Quick Summoning, or by having Quick Summoning 2 plus a Summoning Haste 3 or 4 item.
<br />

<br />
2. As soon as pet root lands, you will need to spam /pet back off, or alternately use /pet hold if you have that skill trained.
<br />

<br />
3. The moment the mob summons your pet, reclaim it, and recast as per the first post in this series. You will need to type the /pet kill &lt;first few letters of the mob's name&gt; while recasting, and hit Enter the moment the pet is finished resummoning. There is nearly ZERO room for delay. If you delay, you may get summoned before the new pet starts engaging the mob.
<br />

<br />
Good luck, and have fun with your new chaining skills.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
